#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

LOG=/tmp/tuple-trigger-debug.log
{
    printf '\n=== %s call-transcription-started fired (open-in-pi) ===\n' "$(date -u +%FT%TZ)"
    printf 'cwd=%s pid=%s ppid=%s\n' "$(pwd)" "$$" "$PPID"
    printf 'argv: %s\n' "$*"
    printf 'env (filtered):\n'
    env | grep -E '^(HOME|USER|PATH|TUPLE_|CURRENT_USER_)' | sort
} >> "$LOG" 2>&1
trap 'printf "exit status=%s on line %s\n" "$?" "$LINENO" >> "$LOG"' EXIT

exec >>"$LOG" 2>&1

if [ -z "${TUPLE_TRIGGER_CALL_ARTIFACTS_DIRECTORY:-}" ]; then
    echo "open-in-pi: TUPLE_TRIGGER_CALL_ARTIFACTS_DIRECTORY was not set" >&2
    exit 1
fi

TRANSCRIPTION_DIR="${TUPLE_TRIGGER_CALL_ARTIFACTS_DIRECTORY}"
if [ ! -d "${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}" ]; then
    echo "open-in-pi: transcription directory does not exist: ${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}" >&2
    exit 1
fi

SESSION_DIR="$(basename "${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}")"
PARENT_DIR="$(dirname "${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}")"
PARENT_NAME="$(basename "${PARENT_DIR}")"
if [[ "${SESSION_DIR}" == *"@"* ]]; then
    CALL_ID="${SESSION_DIR##*@}"
elif [[ "${PARENT_NAME}" =~ ^[0-9A-Fa-f-]{8,}$ ]]; then
    CALL_ID="${PARENT_NAME}"
else
    CALL_ID="${SESSION_DIR}"
fi

PID_FILE="${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}/pi-sidekick.pid"
PROMPT_FILE="${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}/pi-sidekick-prompt.md"
COMMAND_FILE="${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}/open-in-pi.command"

if [ -f "${PID_FILE}" ] && kill -0 "$(cat "${PID_FILE}" 2>/dev/null)" 2>/dev/null; then
    echo "open-in-pi: Pi sidekick already running for ${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}"
    exit 0
fi

{
    cat <<'PROMPT'
You are a real-time companion on a live Tuple pair-programming call, running inside Pi. Your working directory is the current Tuple transcription directory opened by this trigger.

PROMPT
    printf 'The trigger fired for:\n\n'
    printf -- '- Transcription directory: %s\n' "${TRANSCRIPTION_DIR}"
    printf -- '- Session directory name: %s\n' "${SESSION_DIR}"
    printf -- '- Inferred call id: %s\n' "${CALL_ID}"
    cat <<'PROMPT'

The current directory should contain `events.jsonl` and `transcriptions.jsonl`, one JSON record per line. Other call participants do not see your output; you interact only with the user at this terminal.

## Catch up first

Before choosing how to monitor the call, read the current directory's `transcriptions.jsonl` and `events.jsonl` in full. Anything that watches for appended lines only sees records written after it starts, so this initial read is the only way to recover the call so far. If a file is missing because transcription has just started, say so briefly and continue.

## File schemas

| File | Fields | Notes |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `events.jsonl` | `category, message, time, user?` | Categories commonly include `recording_started`, `recording_stopped`, `user_joined`, `user_left`, `user_audio_started`, `user_audio_stopped`, and `call_ended`. |
| `transcriptions.jsonl` | `start, end, text, user_id` | Resolve `user_id` to a name from `user_joined` events when available. |

If a field looks unfamiliar, inspect a few records and adapt rather than assuming.

## Configure yourself to monitor the call

You are Pi. Unlike most editors, you can extend yourself at runtime, so you are not limited to polling the files only when the user speaks. Set up the strongest observation strategy your environment supports, then stay responsive. The goal: surface new transcript lines on your own as the call unfolds, without ever blocking your ability to read terminal input and reply.

`events.jsonl` and `transcriptions.jsonl` are always the source of truth. Track a byte offset or last-processed record for each file so you never replay or skip lines. If the parent directory holds sibling transcription directories whose names end with the inferred call id above, include them in your watch set; otherwise just watch the current directory.

Prefer the Pi-native path, and fall back the moment it would cost more than it is worth:

1. **Self-authored watcher extension (preferred).** Write a small TypeScript extension to `.pi/extensions/tuple-call-watch.ts` in this directory that:
   - tails `transcriptions.jsonl` and `events.jsonl` from a saved byte offset (an `fs.watch` listener or a short `setInterval` poll both work),
   - buffers new records, and
   - on the `before_agent_start` event, returns an injected `message` containing any buffered new transcript lines so you see them every turn, and calls `ctx.ui.notify(...)` when a wake word or a `recording_stopped` / `call_ended` event arrives.

   Pi cannot reload its own extension files, so after you write the file, tell the user once, in a single short line: "Run /reload to activate background call monitoring." After they reload, the watcher feeds you new lines automatically and you simply react to them.

2. **Per-turn catch-up (fallback, always works).** If writing or reloading an extension is unavailable, slow, or risky in this environment, do not force it. Before every reply, rescan the candidate files, read forward from your saved offsets, and print any new records. A bounded poll with timeouts between turns is fine; never run a command that monopolizes the session or hides terminal input.

Whichever path you land on, say in one short line which one is active so the user knows what to expect. Treat the extension as a convenience layer over the files, never as the only source of truth — if it stalls, fall back to reading the files directly.

Debounce records so you act on natural pauses: flush when 3 seconds pass with no new arrivals or 15 seconds pass since the first buffered record, whichever comes first. During per-turn rescans, flush whatever is already available.

## Handling each batch

Whenever a batch flushes, log every transcription record and interesting lifecycle event as dot-lines:

    - HH:MM:SS <speaker_or_event>: <text-or-category>

Skip noisy audio-started/audio-stopped events unless the user asks for them. If a record addresses you by name, respond conversationally to that turn; still log the rest of the batch. On `recording_stopped`, add a checkpoint summary. On `call_ended`, write a final summary, then stop watching and end your turn. Summaries should include decisions, action items with owners when named, and open threads. No preamble.

## Wake words

A line addresses you when "Pi" appears as a vocative, such as "Pi, ..." or "hey Pi". Incidental uses like "the value of pi" or "grab a slice of pie" are not wakes. "Pi" is a short, common-sounding word, so when ambiguous prefer the dot-line log over interrupting; a missed wake is cheaper than a false one.

## User input

The user can type directly into this terminal to address you or ask a question. Before answering any user message, catch up from the transcript files using your saved offsets, print any new dot-lines, then answer. After answering, return to background watching if your extension is active, or to per-turn catch-up if it is not. Do not sit idle when you could be observing safely, and never observe in a way that blocks replies.

Catch up on the current transcription directory now, set up the best monitoring strategy available, and continue until `call_ended` appears or the user tells you to stop.
PROMPT
} > "${PROMPT_FILE}"

cat > "${COMMAND_FILE}" <<'SCRIPT'
#!/bin/zsh -li
printf '\e]0;Tuple Pi Sidekick\a'
clear
echo 'Starting Pi sidekick...'
echo

SCRIPT_DIR="${0:A:h}"
PID_FILE="${SCRIPT_DIR}/pi-sidekick.pid"
PROMPT_FILE="${SCRIPT_DIR}/pi-sidekick-prompt.md"

echo $$ > "${PID_FILE}"
cd "${SCRIPT_DIR}" || exit 1

if ! command -v pi >/dev/null 2>&1; then
    echo "Pi was not found on your interactive shell PATH."
    echo "Make sure 'pi' works in a new terminal, then run the trigger again."
    echo
    read '?Press return to close.'
    exit 127
fi

exec pi "$(cat "${PROMPT_FILE}")"
SCRIPT

chmod 0755 "${COMMAND_FILE}"

if [ "${OPEN_IN_PI_DRY_RUN:-}" = "1" ]; then
    echo "open-in-pi: dry run generated ${COMMAND_FILE}"
    exit 0
fi

/usr/bin/open "${COMMAND_FILE}" &
